In theory, it is possible that signal coming from the purkinje cells shaped. it can actually try to modulate the DCN to inhibit the IO in a way that creates a very unsmooth code which would complexify the spinal chord readout to the point we lose any smoothness/generalization ability of the system. But first as itself backprop has not that much interest in doing so, making the code worse than high dimenssional representation, as the backprop has interest to keep the dimensionality similar or smaller than what is the IO and to keep the code stable (stable in my sens of stable, between trials) because this correspond by definitio to the minimal error possible.

But if even that is not enough we have a strong weapon, we can have a second term in the gradient with a lighter push than the minimization of error in the IO. We can have synaptic decay or even better regularization in the DCN aiming for code that is more similar between DCN units (more uniform code). This will push to find solutions that are way smoother that will backprop produce by itself, a form of generalization. but the code will be only as uniform as what is needed to correct the high dimensional complex code of the IO neurons which contains all the implicit correlation in the sensory/motor/proprioceptive feedbacks/inputs. 

This is just another way we can enforce smootheness/interpolation from the DCN code to ease the output reading from the spinal chord and increase alot the probability that the cerrebellum will input a vector that make sens after a twitch.

